t84.text: The Wet Tropics region is home to about a third of Australia's 315 mammal species. The Wet Tropics Management Authority is working to build the resilience of the world's oldest rainforest to protect animals like the spotted-tailed quoll with its Climate Adaptation Plan.

t85.text: Once common throughout south-eastern Australia, they are now endangered due to loss of habitat and are also under threat from the impacts of climate change.

t86.text: They have a large home range and can cover more than six kilometres overnight, while their den sites are found in rock crevices, caves, hollow logs, burrows and tree hollows.

t87.text: Spotted-tailed quolls hunt mostly at night, being largely nocturnal and solitary. Their diet consists primarily of medium-sized mammals including gliders, possums, rabbits, and even small wallabies. They like carrion (dead animals), birds and eggs as well.

t88.text: The largest marsupial carnivore on mainland Australia, spotted-tail quolls are more than 50 per cent larger than other quolls (eastern, western and northern) and are found in a range of forest environments, from rainforest to open woodland.
